sec.p:
In order to promote structural diversity, targets were only retained if they were found in at least two different publications. Activities were assigned to active and inactive classes according to their protein family using activity thresholds as defined by the Illuminating the Druggable Genome consortium (IDG) [32] (Table 1). We treated each target as follows:
If the target had at least 40 active and 30 inactive compounds using the criteria in Table 1, it was retained for modelling;
If the protein target did not match condition (1) the compounds were divided into active/inactive sets using a default activity threshold of 6.5 logarithmic value units. If this enabled the target to meet criterion (1) then the protein target was retained. This threshold was shown to provide a balanced distribution of active and inactive compounds in the version 20 of ChEMBL [33], and this trend was confirmed for ChEMBL_23 (data not shown);
If the protein target did not match any of the previous criteria then it was discarded.
